<item>
            <title>[LU-6686] tshark drops &apos;ost_lvb&apos; from LDLM_ENQUEUE reply verbose output</title>
                <link>https://jira.whamcloud.com/browse/LU-6686</link>
                <project id="10000" key="LU">Lustre</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;Attached is a tcpdump for an experiment running an &apos;fstat&apos; (&apos;multiop OSc&apos;) from the client. Look for the LDLM_ENQUEUE (intent : getattr) request and reply, then go on to the next LDLM_ENQUEUE request and reply. The latter is a request from the client to the OST for an extent lock. The reply is listed in the header as having three buffers:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;  Lm Bufflens: 152 - ptlrpc_body&lt;br/&gt;
  Lm Bufflens: 112 - ldlm_reply&lt;br/&gt;
  Lm Bufflens:  56 - ?what?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The third buffer is not included in the output at all. This is after an update with &lt;a href=&quot;http://review.whamcloud.com/#/c/14961/&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;http://review.whamcloud.com/#/c/14961/&lt;/a&gt; . Prior to that update the verbose output to tshark said &quot;generic data&quot;. Now it doesn&apos;t even say that. I am pretty sure this is supposed to be a &apos;struct ost_lvb&apos; (which is 56 bytes), but can&apos;t be absolutely sure. &lt;br/&gt;
-Andrew&lt;/p&gt;</description>
